<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12067c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12067c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12067c"> 67(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> SK&apos;s wife / et uxor eius / = any married W / = wife of deacon porter</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">124-5: St. Patrick <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> visited <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Armagh, where he convened a Synod and drew up a number of canons for the better government of the Catholic Church in Ireland <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is commanded in one reading of the sixth of these canons that the wives of clerics when abroad must wear veils. Harris <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> endeavours to deduce from this <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> that celibacy was not enjoined on the Irish clergy during the life of St. Patrick.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Dr. Do?llinger, however, points out distinctly that the words refer, not to priests, but to the inferior clergy in minor Orders, who were not bound by the vow of celibacy. The decree runs as follows: &lsquo;Quicunque clericus ab ostiario usque ad sacerdotem sine tunica visus fuerit, etc., et ejus uxor, si non velato capite ambulaverit,&rsquo; etc. (Any cleric &hellip; from a porter to a priest &hellip; and his wife &hellip; &lsquo;et uxor,&rsquo; without the &lsquo;ejus&rsquo; &hellip; refers to married women generally. <small> William Canon Fleming, <a name="WFSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WFSP"><cite title="source">The Life of St Patrick: Apostle of Ireland</cite></a> (1905) 125</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
